post_text:
We know many of our staff, families and community members have been forced to evacuate from our homes on a moment's notice, some left without power and internet, and others are still not home or have even lost a home due to these fires. Many of you have lent a hand and opened your homes to neighbors, friends, and co-workers to help them out in a time of need and some of us have been the beneficiary of this generosity.

In times like these, it is important that we, as parents and educators, monitor our children’s reactions, and gauge our response accordingly. Our school staff is here to assist should your child need additional emotional support.

As planned, distance learning will resume tomorrow, Monday, August 24. Additionally, meal distribution will continue at Cambridge, Foxboro, Scandia, and Vanden. If you, or your family, have been affected by the wildfires or power outages and need flexibility around class participation or classwork, please inform your teacher.

post_text:
UPDATE 8.20.20 9:45am:
Due to current conditions, there will be no meal distribution Friday, August 21.

UPDATE 8.19.20 2:35pm:
Due to the evacuations, power outages, and air quality in our local area all instruction, both live and online, is canceled Thursday, August 20 through Friday, August 21. We want you and our staff to be able to focus on families during this time.

At this time, we expect Distance Learning to resume as normal on Monday, August 24 and we will update you if conditions change.

Stay Safe, Stay Healthy,

Due to the fires currently taking place, you, your family members, or your teacher(s) may be affected. If this is the case, please take care of your family and do not worry about school.

Your teacher(s) may have connection issues and may not meet your child this morning for class. They may not be able to inform you. If this occurs, students can continue to work on previously assigned work.

At this time classes are not being canceled district-wide and meals will be available at Foxboro, Cambridge, Vanden, and Scandia.

Our thoughts are with you and your families.

The California Independent System Operator (ISO) has issued a statewide Flex Alert to be in effect from 3-10pm each day through Wednesday.

While the daily Flex Alert takes place after school hours, we understand that they may affect students' ability to connect to their Google classroom or complete assignments.

Should your household be affected by a rotating electric outage, any absences that occur as a result will be excused and deadlines for assignments will be extended. Please make your child's teacher aware of any power outages you may incur due to the Flex Alert in place through Wednesday, Aug. 19, that has interfered with class or classwork.

The link below provides information regarding the Flex Alert and how to prepare.
Stay Safe

Fairfield PAL is putting on a college prep program! Check it out:
Do you want to know how to win the college game?
Thanks to Professor Padilla-Alvarado, Fairfield PAL has the playbook and can share it with you! Apply now to join them on Thursdays in July and August and learn all the tactics to win the college game! This class is FREE, but space is limited!
Open to Fairfield, Suisun, and Travis students who have completed grades 8-11, with priority seating for students who have completed 10th grade or participated in previous Ready to Succeed workshops.
Call 422-6288 to apply. A FREE Fairfield PAL membership is required.
#CollegePrep #CollegeReady #FirstGeneration
This program is made possible with support from the Fairfield-Suisun Rotary Club.

post_text:
Travis USD has received authorization to provide meals through the month of June. Meals will be distributed Mondays and Thursdays at one location: Travis Education Center (TEC) (2775 De Ronde Dr, Fairfield).

Meals will be distributed as follows:
- All children 18 and under will be able to receive meals, regardless of what school/district they attend
- Distribution time is 11:00am – 12:30pm
- Monday's meals will include lunches for Mon - Wed and breakfasts for Tues - Thurs
Thursday's meals will include lunches for Thur - Sun and breakfasts for Fri - Mon (including weekends)
- Service will be grab and go style, with no eating at the site.
- Federal government requires that all children must be present to be served and only one pickup per day per child is allowed.

We would like to congratulate Sarah Bergendahl, Anthony Mendoza, Harkeerat Singh for being named 2019-2020 "American Legion National School Award" winners by American Legion Post 165 & the American Legion Auxiliary Unit 165.

The American Legion National school award is the highest youth honor presented by the American Legion to deserving students each year. Selected students attended and completed their Boys State / Girls State sessions, completed community service, attended required activities and reported back to their community on their experiences while at their respective sessions.

Travis USD has added weekend meals to our meal distribution locations. Meals will be distributed at both Travis Education Center (TEC) (2775 De Ronde Dr, Fairfield) and Foxboro (600 Morning Glory Dr, Vacaville).

Meals will be distributed as follows:
- All children 18 and under will be able to receive meals, regardless of what school/district they attend
- Distribution time is 11:00am – 12:30pm
- Lunch will be served along with breakfast for the following day. Friday's meals will include lunches for Friday, Saturday and Sunday and breakfasts for Saturday, Sunday, and Monday
- Service will be grab and go style, with no eating at the site.
- Federal government requires that all children must be present to be served and only one pickup per day per child is allowed.

post_text:
Last week our baseball players and parents prepared and delivered meals to Vacaville Fire Dept and Fairfield Fire Department Fire Houses, NorthBay Healthcare in Vacaville and Fairfield and Kaiser Vacaville Emergency, Rad,Lab, and HBS departments. The food was initially purchased for the Baseball Hot Stove Event which was cancelled due to the coronavirus pandemic.
“I am constantly amazed at our students’ and families’ generosity and willingness to serve,” says Travis USD Board President Ivery Hood. “Though I shouldn’t be because it happens repeatedly. I couldn’t be prouder to part of this amazing district!”

April 28th 5pm – 6pm
Supporting Children’s Mental Health
and Wellbeing During COVID-19

This training will provide parents/caregivers with an opportunity to gain information related to some of the effects that COVID-19 could have in children’s mental health and how their wellbeing can be supported. Along with pointers on how parents/caregivers can present the information to children in a way that will allow them to feel safe and supported.
Objectives:
 Identify emotional and mental health effects of COVID-19 in
children.
 Presenting information in a child-friendly and age appropriate manner.
 Creating a safe space for children

Please register with Elle Abundis at eabundis@abetterwayinc.net

post_text:
Travis USD Families,
I hope this communication finds you and your family well. Solano County Superintendents and Charter School Administrators have made a unified decision to extend school closures through May 1, 2020 . This is a coordinated response that represents a continued effort to reduce the number of affected individuals with COVID-19 and to keep our communities as safe as possible. For more information, please visit our website at www.travisusd.org.

I know that these are challenging times for all of us and my heart goes out to each and every one of you. Please know that TUSD will do all that we can to keep you up to date. We are currently working with our teachers to develop a comprehensive remote learning plan and will provide information once that plan is fully developed.

Thank you for your continued flexibility and patience as we work through this,

Fondly,
Pam Conklin
Superintendent
#togetherwecan

We want to thank our TUSD families for their patience, flexibility, and cooperation during this unprecedented situation.

Travis Unified School District continues to cooperate with state and local agencies to align efforts to combat the spread of COVID-19. It is in this spirit that the Travis USD school closure will be extended through April 17, 2020. This will take us through our Spring Break which will not be rescheduled.

Please continue to visit our website and follow our Facebook page to receive updates. Please know that we are thinking of you and your family during these stressful times. TUSD hopes to serve as a resource to you and we will do our best to provide any and all information as we receive guidance and direction.

shared_text:
Brent Manuel
March 8 at 6:43 AM ·

What a crazy busy weekend. We took 33 students to Utah to compete in the FIRST Robotics Utah Regional Competition. In the end we placed down in the ranks, but were picked up by the fourth team alliance. We made to the semifinals before losing.

There are many things happening at these events in addition to the robot. There are judges wandering the venue asking teams questions about business plans, engineering notebooks, safety features, and more. We have team who presents Chairman's a contest where we showcase our outreach, growth and more. At one point we had judges in the pit, talking to the team, in the stands and up in the main stands.

At the end of the day we won the Safety Award and the Engineering Inspiration Award. The Engineering Inspiration Award gives us an automatic bid to Worlds in Houston and our entry fee is being paid for by NASA.

GO ROBOVIKES #701

post_text:
On February 18, 2020, the District and TUTA met again for negotiations. Unfortunately, the teams were unable to reach agreement on remaining issues. The teams are very far apart on significant financial issues. The District has repeatedly expressed its belief that many of TUTA’s economic proposals are not fiscally responsible.
At the end of the session, the District shared that it will file a request with the Public Employment Relations Board (PERB) tomorrow to proceed to impasse mediation (more on impasse, below). TUTA stated that it agreed that the teams were at impasse.
Visit our website (travisusd.org) for more...

post_text:
OUR KIDS ARE WORTH THE WAIT!
The yellow flashing lights warn you to slow down and prepare to stop. When the bus flashes red lights, you must stop from either direction until the children are safely across the street and the lights stop flashing. The law requires you remain stopped as long as the red lights are flashing (CVC §22454). If you fail to stop, you may be fined up to $1,000 and your driving privilege could be suspended for 1 year. If the school bus is on the other side of a divided or multilane highway (two or more lanes in each direction), you do not need to stop.

post_text: The Travis Unified School District, together with the Fairfield Police Department, will hold a press conference today at 9:30am to provide information around the decision to close Vanden High School. The press conference will be held at the District Office which is located at 2751 De Ronde Drive.

The first two “Lunch with the Principal” days this March. These Foxes demonstrated our core values and chose to place their Character Champion awards in the bag to be selected to eat lunch with Mrs. Chizauskie and Miss Andrews. Ms. Lyn even made us homemade chocolate chip cookies to make the celebration even more special! 💜🦊 Travis Unified School District
